1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,425
Time series is another popular data format for storing data over time.

2
00:00:04,425 --> 00:00:07,515
It's a sequence of data points collected at regular time intervals,

3
00:00:07,515 --> 00:00:09,285
often used to analyze trends,

4
00:00:09,285 --> 00:00:11,475
patterns, and forecasting overtime.

5
00:00:11,475 --> 00:00:13,950
Let's take a look at the steps data wrangler is used to

6
00:00:13,950 --> 00:00:16,960
deal with dates and pandas and clean time-series data.

7
00:00:16,960 --> 00:00:20,100
We'll start with importing our Pandas and NumPy packages.

8
00:00:20,100 --> 00:00:23,700
For this demo, we'll be using a hypothetical stock dataset that's modeled

9
00:00:23,700 --> 00:00:27,060
after the popular Apple stock dataset that contains two columns.

10
00:00:27,060 --> 00:00:30,000
The first column is the date for everyday between Jan 1,

11
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:32,700
2018 to March 1, 2021.

12
00:00:32,700 --> 00:00:36,595
The date is known in the ear of month and date format.

13
00:00:36,595 --> 00:00:39,020
The second column is volume in millions,

14
00:00:39,020 --> 00:00:41,600
denoting the number of shares traded during the trading day.

15
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:44,480
Let's start with some simple inspection of this data.

16
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:47,285
As we can see with the results of the describe method,

17
00:00:47,285 --> 00:00:53,195
the volume columns values typically range from 10 to about 600 million.

18
00:00:53,195 --> 00:00:54,770
Using the info method,

19
00:00:54,770 --> 00:00:57,080
we can see that the date column has a date

20
00:00:57,080 --> 00:01:00,410
type object because the dates were stored as strings.

21
00:01:00,410 --> 00:01:05,920
The datatype of the volume column is into 64 as all the values are numerical.

22
00:01:05,920 --> 00:01:08,360
Let's also plot our time series data.

23
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:11,210
We can do this by running df dot plot on our DataFrame,

24
00:01:11,210 --> 00:01:14,315
plotting the data as the x-axis and the volume is the y-axis.

25
00:01:14,315 --> 00:01:16,340
To visualize our time series data,

26
00:01:16,340 --> 00:01:19,325
we can see that the data has a lot of dips and peaks.

27
00:01:19,325 --> 00:01:21,950
Now let's get started with the wrangling process.

28
00:01:21,950 --> 00:01:24,170
Our first immediate step should be to convert

29
00:01:24,170 --> 00:01:27,125
the date column from an object to a pandas date-time.

30
00:01:27,125 --> 00:01:29,150
We can easily manipulate the date.

31
00:01:29,150 --> 00:01:32,840
We can do this using the two DateTime method on our date column.

32
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:35,165
Looking at the outputs of dot info again,

33
00:01:35,165 --> 00:01:38,780
the datatype of date is now a day times 64 ns.

34
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:42,140
Ns means the nanosecond based time format

35
00:01:42,140 --> 00:01:44,905
specifying the precision of the datetime object.

36
00:01:44,905 --> 00:01:47,000
Now, with this datetime object,

37
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,585
we can actually do a lot of interesting operations now on the time.

38
00:01:50,585 --> 00:01:52,355
Let's go two examples.

39
00:01:52,355 --> 00:01:55,565
First, if I want to know how much time is captured by my dataset,

40
00:01:55,565 --> 00:01:58,460
I can use the max and min functions on

41
00:01:58,460 --> 00:02:03,385
my date column to see that the data captures 1,155 days.

42
00:02:03,385 --> 00:02:07,895
If I want to extract information from the date columns such as the year, for example,

43
00:02:07,895 --> 00:02:11,990
for eventually merging this data with another data table that also has a year column,

44
00:02:11,990 --> 00:02:14,890
I can actually use this dt oxidizer by

45
00:02:14,890 --> 00:02:18,435
denoting dt dot year to get the year of the datetime object.

46
00:02:18,435 --> 00:02:21,410
Here I'm assigning it to a new column in our tiny DataFrame.

47
00:02:21,410 --> 00:02:24,470
Now know how much easier this is than having to use

48
00:02:24,470 --> 00:02:27,680
string manipulations to extract the year from the date.

49
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:30,710
Here I've created a separate year column pretty simply.

50
00:02:30,710 --> 00:02:34,490
Now next comes the critical step with manipulating time series data.

51
00:02:34,490 --> 00:02:36,440
Setting the index as our date column,

52
00:02:36,440 --> 00:02:40,400
which we can typically do right after converting the column to a datetime object.

53
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:43,820
This turns the date column into a date-time index,

54
00:02:43,820 --> 00:02:48,670
as we can see with the outputs of the dot info method and the dot index method.

55
00:02:48,670 --> 00:02:51,185
Here we use set index and our date column,

56
00:02:51,185 --> 00:02:52,590
turning it into an index.

57
00:02:52,590 --> 00:02:56,110
We can check the type of the index using dot index.

58
00:02:56,110 --> 00:02:57,995
Here we confirm it's a date-time index.

59
00:02:57,995 --> 00:03:01,340
If we don't see any index or date variable for this DataFrame,

60
00:03:01,340 --> 00:03:03,140
we're going to run into a few limitations.

61
00:03:03,140 --> 00:03:06,230
For example, we can do one thing which is called resampling.

62
00:03:06,230 --> 00:03:09,020
A very powerful and popular method that's similar to

63
00:03:09,020 --> 00:03:12,390
a group by but for time series. Let's look into that.

64
00:03:12,390 --> 00:03:14,400
Resampling can do two main things,

65
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:19,000
provide a time-based grouping with a target frequency and aggregate based on that.

66
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:22,865
Let's say I want to get the yearly mean volume in my dataset.

67
00:03:22,865 --> 00:03:26,990
We're going to do this by resampling by first using DFS on re-sample Y,

68
00:03:26,990 --> 00:03:28,180
where Y is the year.

69
00:03:28,180 --> 00:03:31,520
This is the rule parameters specifying our target for the conversion.

70
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:37,145
Then I'll use dot mean on the volume to get the yearly average volume in my dataset.

71
00:03:37,145 --> 00:03:38,435
Take a look at the results.

72
00:03:38,435 --> 00:03:42,815
I can now see the mean volume from my dataset for each year.

73
00:03:42,815 --> 00:03:47,300
We can actually plot these results by simply attaching dotplot to the end of this block,

74
00:03:47,300 --> 00:03:51,740
and now we have a line plot of the results and an yearly rather than daily granularity.

75
00:03:51,740 --> 00:03:53,350
Here's another handy method.

76
00:03:53,350 --> 00:03:56,705
Let's say I'd like to get what day of the week the date falls on.

77
00:03:56,705 --> 00:04:01,190
I can use day of week on my index to get whether the day is a Monday,

78
00:04:01,190 --> 00:04:03,320
a Tuesday, and so on until Sunday,

79
00:04:03,320 --> 00:04:05,225
where Monday is zero, Tuesday one,

80
00:04:05,225 --> 00:04:09,260
Sunday is six, then I can do things like get all the rows for the days are

81
00:04:09,260 --> 00:04:15,160
a Monday as I can do here with isin function and get the mean volume across all Mondays.

82
00:04:15,160 --> 00:04:18,560
Now, what about manipulating our new date-time index further?

83
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:22,160
We can also convert our date variable to a specified format.

84
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:24,650
Here I make a copy of my DataFrame so I don't

85
00:04:24,650 --> 00:04:27,275
influence the original date-time index, that's neat.

86
00:04:27,275 --> 00:04:33,920
I then use the string F time on my DataFrames index specifying the following format.

87
00:04:33,920 --> 00:04:35,855
Percent B means full month name,

88
00:04:35,855 --> 00:04:37,355
percent d means day of the month,

89
00:04:37,355 --> 00:04:38,765
then followed by a comment.

90
00:04:38,765 --> 00:04:40,775
Finally, percent Y means year.

91
00:04:40,775 --> 00:04:43,580
For example, we are turning our date format from the year, month,

92
00:04:43,580 --> 00:04:47,765
day to the January 1, 2018 format.

93
00:04:47,765 --> 00:04:51,715
As we can see here, the index is successfully modified.

94
00:04:51,715 --> 00:04:53,445
Here's another cool thing.

95
00:04:53,445 --> 00:04:56,615
If we don't set the index as our date variable for this DataFrame,

96
00:04:56,615 --> 00:05:00,325
we would have been forced to use the.dt accessor.

97
00:05:00,325 --> 00:05:03,920
For example, in order to convert our date variable to a specific format,

98
00:05:03,920 --> 00:05:09,875
we would have had to use DFT date indexing on the date column dt dot strip time.

99
00:05:09,875 --> 00:05:14,090
Let's talk about one last thing with cleaning time series data, missing data.

100
00:05:14,090 --> 00:05:16,100
Take a look at this new DataFrame I loaded.

101
00:05:16,100 --> 00:05:18,710
Again, one of the first types of cleaning time series data is

102
00:05:18,710 --> 00:05:21,860
converting your day column to datetime objects.

103
00:05:21,860 --> 00:05:26,495
We can see that there's a number of NA values by using is na method,

104
00:05:26,495 --> 00:05:29,410
and we can actually sum up the number of values as well.

105
00:05:29,410 --> 00:05:32,090
If you want, you can investigate this missing data further

106
00:05:32,090 --> 00:05:34,850
using few of the methods we discussed above and others,

107
00:05:34,850 --> 00:05:37,190
for example using the day of the week method to figure

108
00:05:37,190 --> 00:05:39,845
out which days have missing data in your dataset.

109
00:05:39,845 --> 00:05:42,545
Let's actually jump to filling these missing values.

110
00:05:42,545 --> 00:05:44,900
We can use the fill NA function,

111
00:05:44,900 --> 00:05:46,210
as we're familiar with,

112
00:05:46,210 --> 00:05:48,480
and specify how we'd like to fill the values.

113
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:50,795
For example, we could use the mean or the median.

114
00:05:50,795 --> 00:05:53,585
Here, I use the ffill perimeter,

115
00:05:53,585 --> 00:05:58,790
which replaces each missing value with the previous valid value in the same column.

116
00:05:58,790 --> 00:06:01,505
After running this, if we check the number of Na's again,

117
00:06:01,505 --> 00:06:05,870
notice how the number of Na's have disappeared after our filename.

118
00:06:05,870 --> 00:06:08,630
We would typically extend this analysis by then doing

119
00:06:08,630 --> 00:06:13,200
a detailed programmatic assessment to confirm that the Na values are gone.

